solutions.content:
For this problem I decided to go straight for an array approach to build a frequency table of all the seen characters and then iterate again to find the first with a frequency of only `1`.

To do so, I created 2 support variables:
* `len` to store the length of the string;
* `alpha`, the aforementioned frequency table, with a size of `127`, making the char code of `'z'`, the last character in our range.

We will then move first of all to populate `alpha` increasing the cell matching each character by `1` as we go.

We will then loop through the string another time, this time just checking if the frequency is `1`, meaning the character is indeed unique and returning its index in case.

If we exit the loop without a match, we can then safely conclude no uniques were there and return `-1` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int firstUniqChar(string s) {
        // support variables
        int len = s.size(), alpha[127] = {};
		// populating alpha
        for (char c: s) alpha[c]++;
		// hunting for unique elements
        for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
            if (alpha[s[i]] == 1) return i;
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

Variation using an array of only `26` characters, making it less memory consuming, but also a bit slower due to the extra burden of normalising each character to be in the `0 - 25` range:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int firstUniqChar(string s) {
        // support variables
        int len = s.size(), alpha[26] = {};
		// populating alpha
        for (char c: s) alpha[c - 'a']++;
		// hunting for unique elements
        for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
            if (alpha[s[i] - 'a'] == 1) return i;
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

Further variation where I iterate building up `alpha` while at the same time updating a `seenTwice` variable - once that hits `26` overall seen characters, it means we cannot get any matches and it does not make any sense to loop further:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int firstUniqChar(string s) {
        // support variables
        int len = s.size(), alpha[127] = {}, seenTwice = 0;
		// populating alpha as long as it is needed
        for (char c: s) {
            if (alpha[c] == 1) seenTwice++;
            if (seenTwice == 26) return -1;
            alpha[c]++;
        }
		// hunting for unique elements
        for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
            if (alpha[s[i]] == 1) return i;
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

