Algo 1: Run on given string, find frequency of each element. Than run again over string, the first character having frequency 1 is your answer. 
Complexity : (2*n) => O(n)

```
 public int firstUniqCharTwiceIteration(String s) {

        if ( s == null || s.isEmpty())
            return -1; 

        int [] freq = new int [26] ; 

        for (char c : s.toCharArray()){
            int x = c - 'a'; 
            freq[x]++;
        }

        int i =0;
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()){
            int x = c - 'a'; 
            if(freq[x]==1)
                return i; 

                i++;
        }
        return -1;
    }
```

Algo 2: Run over given string, store the "First index" of each character. If a character is repeated, then push -1.
Run over frequency array, and find the least index value. 

Complexity: O(26+n) => O(n)

```
  public int firstUniqCharSingleIteration(String s) {
          if ( s == null || s.isEmpty())
            return -1; 

        int [] freq = new int [26] ; 

        for (int i = 0; i<s.length(); i++){
            int x = s.charAt(i) - 'a'; 

            if(freq[x] == 0)
                freq[x] = i+1; 
            else 
                freq[x] = -1; 
        }

        int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int i =0; i < 26; i++){
            if ( freq[i] >0 )
                min = Math.min(min, freq[i]-1); 

        }

        return min==Integer.MAX_VALUE ? -1 : min;

    }
```

Algo 3: Iterate over a to z, find the 
1. Find the first index and last index of this character.
2. Choose min ( min, First) So far if first = last

Complexity: O(26*n)
However this is 100% fast and run in 1 ms (supersingly ) 
```
public int firstUniqCharIteration(String s) {
        if(s == null || s.isEmpty()) return -1;
        int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        for(char c = 'a'; c <= 'z'; c++) {
            int first = s.indexOf(c);
            int last = s.lastIndexOf(c);

            if(first != -1 && first == last) {
                min = Math.min(min, first);
            }
        }
        return min == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? -1 : min;
    }
```

I believe the fastest one should be the Algo 2 as it has the least complexity O(26+n)
But, on leetcode the third algo is fastest.

